## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P3 · FEA · Claude-A

The `transport::Atomic<T>` wrapper and the lock-free channel primitives (`transport::SpscQueue<T>`, `transport::MpmcQueue<T>`, `transport::SeqLock<T>`) are defined in headers that unconditionally `#include <atomic>` and use `std::atomic<T>` with `memory_order_acquire` / `memory_order_release` semantics. These headers are included transitively by any translation unit that touches pub/sub channel infrastructure.

### The Problem

Not all Cyber RT world model translation units execute on hardware with native atomic support. Specifically:

1. **Code generation / metaprogramming TUs**: The `tools/codegen` pipeline generates protobuf message stubs for individual state types. These stubs `#include "transport/channel.h"` to access `ChannelId` type aliases, but `codegen` runs on the host at build time, and some cross-compilation targets (e.g. embedded individual controllers on RISC-V without A extension) lack hardware atomics. Currently, compilation fails with:

```
error: target does not support atomic operations
  → in file included from transport/channel.h:12:
  → transport/atomic.h:34: std::atomic<uint64_t> write_seq;
```

2. **Documentation generation TUs**: The `tools/docgen` pipeline parses transport headers for API documentation extraction. It includes transport headers in a libclang AST parse context that targets a generic architecture without specifying atomic width support.

3. **Static analysis TUs**: The `sysmo` (system monitor) module includes transport headers for channel statistics types but runs as a pure data aggregator with no actual atomic operations — it only reads statistics structs populated by the transport layer.

### Proposed Solution

Introduce a conditional inclusion guard that allows translation units to include transport headers for type definitions without pulling in atomic operations:

```cpp
// transport/atomic.h — current
#include <atomic>

namespace transport {
template <typename T>
using Atomic = std::atomic<T>;
}

// transport/atomic.h — proposed
#if defined(PUBSUB_LOOP_HAS_ATOMICS) || defined(__cpp_lib_atomic_ref)
  #include <atomic>
  namespace transport {
  template <typename T>
  using Atomic = std::atomic<T>;

  // Full lock-free primitives available
  #define PUBSUB_LOOP_TRANSPORT_LOCKFREE 1
  }
#else
  namespace transport {
  // Stub: type-compatible but NOT thread-safe
  // Only for use in build-time tools and static analysis
  template <typename T>
  struct Atomic {
      T value_;
      T load(std::memory_order = std::memory_order_seq_cst) const { return value_; }
      void store(T v, std::memory_order = std::memory_order_seq_cst) { value_ = v; }
      // Compile-time assertion if anyone tries to use this in a concurrent context
      static_assert(!PUBSUB_LOOP_RUNTIME_BUILD, 
          "transport::Atomic stub used in runtime build — define PUBSUB_LOOP_HAS_ATOMICS");
  };

  #define PUBSUB_LOOP_TRANSPORT_LOCKFREE 0
  }
#endif
```

### Lock-free primitive guards

Similarly, the lock-free channel primitives should be gated:

```cpp
// transport/spsc_queue.h
#if PUBSUB_LOOP_TRANSPORT_LOCKFREE

namespace transport {
template <typename T, size_t Capacity>
class SpscQueue {
    // ... full lock-free SPSC implementation
};
}

#else
// When atomics unavailable, SpscQueue is not defined
// TUs that need the type for documentation / codegen can use:
namespace transport {
template <typename T, size_t Capacity>
class SpscQueue;  // forward declaration only
}
#endif
```

### Build system integration

```cmake
# In transport/CMakeLists.txt
include(CheckCXXSourceCompiles)
check_cxx_source_compiles("
    #include <atomic>
    int main() { std::atomic<uint64_t> a{0}; a.fetch_add(1); return 0; }
" PUBSUB_LOOP_HAS_ATOMICS)

if(PUBSUB_LOOP_HAS_ATOMICS)
    target_compile_definitions(transport PUBLIC PUBSUB_LOOP_HAS_ATOMICS=1)
    target_compile_definitions(transport PUBLIC PUBSUB_LOOP_RUNTIME_BUILD=1)
endif()

# Host tools (codegen, docgen) explicitly do NOT define PUBSUB_LOOP_HAS_ATOMICS
# even on platforms that support it, because they don't need atomic operations
target_compile_definitions(codegen_tool PRIVATE PUBSUB_LOOP_RUNTIME_BUILD=0)
```

