## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P3 · on hold · Claude-A

### Background

The `node` module currently defines its own complex-channel type (`node::ComplexChannel<T>`) for carrying composite individual states — states that contain nested sub-individual data, variable-length arrays, or references to other individuals. This type exists separately from the base transport layer's `transport::Message<T>` primitives.

```cpp
// Current: node module's own channel type
namespace node {

template <typename T>
class ComplexChannel {
    // Handles serialization of nested types
    // Handles variable-length fields (e.g. individual's child list)
    // Handles individual-reference resolution
    // Has its own buffer management, separate from transport::PoolAllocator

    void publish(const T& state);
    std::optional<T> read_latest();
};

}  // namespace node
```

The problem: `ComplexChannel<T>` duplicates ~40% of the logic in `transport::ShmWriter<T>` and `transport::RtpsWriter<T>` (buffer management, QoS, sequence numbering) and adds its own serialization layer that does not integrate with `message::Serializer<T>`.

### Why this is on hold

This refactoring depends on two prerequisites that are not yet complete:

1. **Transport EPIC #1** (Unify RTPS and shared-memory backends) — `ComplexChannel` should delegate to `UnifiedWriter<T>`, not directly to individual backends. Replacing it before the unified writer exists would mean rewriting the delegation twice.

2. **Message module nested type support** — `message::Serializer<T>` does not currently handle recursive individual state types (e.g. `IndividualState` containing a `std::vector<SubIndividualState>`). The message module needs to support this before `ComplexChannel`'s custom serialization can be removed.

### Target design (when unblocked)

```cpp
// Target: node::ComplexChannel<T> becomes a thin wrapper
namespace node {

template <typename T>
class ComplexChannel {
public:
    void publish(const T& state) {
        // Step 1: serialize via message module (not custom code)
        auto buf = message::serialize(state);

        // Step 2: publish via unified transport (not custom buffer mgmt)
        unified_writer_.write(std::move(buf));
    }

    std::optional<T> read_latest() {
        auto buf = unified_reader_.read_latest();
        if (!buf) return std::nullopt;
        return message::deserialize<T>(*buf);
    }

private:
    transport::UnifiedWriter<T> unified_writer_;  // from EPIC #1
    transport::UnifiedReader<T> unified_reader_;
};

}  // namespace node
```

### Individual-reference resolution

The one piece of logic that `ComplexChannel` has which transport primitives genuinely don't is **individual-reference resolution**: when an individual's state contains a reference to another individual (e.g. `parent_id`, `target_id`), `ComplexChannel` resolves these references at deserialization time to ensure the referenced individual is still alive.

This should move to a `node::ReferenceResolver` component, not live in the channel:

```cpp
namespace node {

class ReferenceResolver {
public:
    // Validate that all IndividualId references in a state struct are still alive
    // Called after deserialization, before delivering to subscriber
    template <typename T>
    ValidationResult validate_references(const T& state);

    enum class ValidationResult {
        ALL_VALID,
        SOME_STALE,    // referenced individual died — subscriber gets a warning
        CRITICAL_STALE // primary reference (e.g. parent) died — subscriber gets error
    };
};

}  // namespace node
```

