## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P3 · FEA · Claude-C

### Problem

The world model supports individuals that carry AI inference workloads — for example, an individual representing an autonomous agent runs a neural network to decide its next action based on the world state it observes. These inference queries currently follow a request-response pattern over standard pub/sub channels:

```
Current inference flow:

  Agent Individual          Inference Service Individual
       │                              │
       ├── publish(InferenceRequest) ──►│
       │   on /world/agent_42/infer    │
       │                               ├── run neural network
       │                               │   (10-100ms)
       │◄── publish(InferenceResult) ──┤
       │   on /world/agent_42/result   │
       │                               │
```

This works for individual queries but does not scale. When 100 agent individuals each send inference requests at 10Hz, the inference service processes them one-by-one:

```
Sequential processing:
  req_0 ──── 15ms ────┐
                       req_1 ──── 15ms ────┐
                                            req_2 ──── 15ms ────┐
                                                                 ...
  Total for 100 requests: ~1500ms (should be ~20ms batched on GPU)
```

Neural network inference is dramatically more efficient when **batched** — processing 100 inputs in a single GPU kernel launch takes roughly the same time as processing 1. But the current pub/sub channel design has no concept of request batching.

### Proposed Solution

Add a batched inference adapter to the RTPS transport layer that collects individual inference requests over a configurable time window and delivers them as a single batched tensor to the inference service:

```cpp
namespace transport {

// Publisher side: agent individuals use this instead of raw ChannelWriter
template <typename RequestT, typename ResultT>
class InferenceBatchPublisher {
public:
    // Submit an inference request — returns a future for the result
    // The request is queued, not sent immediately
    std::future<ResultT> submit(const RequestT& request);

    // Configuration
    struct BatchConfig {
        size_t max_batch_size = 64;         // max requests per batch
        Duration max_wait = 5ms;            // max time to wait for batch to fill
        Duration timeout = 100ms;           // per-request timeout
        bool pad_incomplete_batches = true; // pad last batch to power-of-2
    };
};

// Subscriber side: inference service receives batched requests
template <typename RequestT, typename ResultT>
class InferenceBatchSubscriber {
public:
    // Called when a batch is ready
    // The service processes all requests in one GPU kernel launch
    using BatchHandler = std::function<std::vector<ResultT>(
        const std::vector<RequestT>& batch)>;

    void set_handler(BatchHandler handler);
};

}  // namespace transport
```

### Batching strategy

```
Batched inference flow:

  Agent 0 ─── req ──┐
  Agent 1 ─── req ──┤
  Agent 2 ─── req ──┤  BatchCollector     Inference Service
  ...               ├─────────────────►  ┌───────────────┐
  Agent 63 ── req ──┤  (waits max 5ms   │ GPU batch     │
                    │   or 64 requests) │ inference     │
                    │                    │ (1 kernel)    │
                    │◄─────────────────  │ ~20ms         │
                    │   batch results    └───────────────┘
  Agent 0 ◄─── res ┤
  Agent 1 ◄─── res ┤
  ...               │
  Agent 63 ◄── res ─┘

  Total for 64 requests: ~25ms (vs ~960ms sequential)
```

### RTPS transport integration

The batch collector is implemented as a transport-layer adapter, transparent to the individual component code:

```cpp
// How it plugs into the transport stack:
//
// ┌────────────────────────────────────┐
// │  Individual Component              │
// │  submit(request) → future<result>  │
// └──────────┬─────────────────────────┘
//            │
// ┌──────────▼─────────────────────────┐
// │  InferenceBatchPublisher           │
// │  ┌──────────────────────┐          │
// │  │ BatchCollector       │          │
// │  │ - accumulates reqs   │          │
// │  │ - triggers on size   │          │
// │  │   or timeout         │          │
// │  └──────────┬───────────┘          │
// │             │ batch ready          │
// │  ┌──────────▼───────────┐          │
// │  │ RTPS DataWriter      │          │
// │  │ (publishes BatchMsg)  │          │
// │  └──────────────────────┘          │
// └────────────────────────────────────┘

// The batch message on the wire:
struct BatchInferenceMessage {
    uint64_t batch_id;
    uint32_t num_requests;
    std::vector<IndividualId> request_sources;  // who sent each request
    std::vector<uint8_t> batched_payload;       // concatenated request tensors
    // Layout: [req_0_tensor | req_1_tensor | ... | req_N_tensor]
    // Each tensor is same size (padded if necessary)
};
```

### Streaming pub/sub channel adapter

For continuous inference (e.g. individuals that need predictions every tick), provide a streaming variant:

```cpp
namespace transport {

// Streaming inference: results are published on a pub/sub channel
// instead of returned via future
template <typename RequestT, typename ResultT>
class StreamingInferenceAdapter {
public:
    // Publish requests on input channel, results appear on output channel
    // Batching is automatic and transparent
    StreamingInferenceAdapter(
        ChannelId input_channel,   // e.g. /world/inference/requests
        ChannelId output_channel,  // e.g. /world/inference/results
        BatchConfig config
    );

    // Individual subscribes to output channel filtered by its own ID
    // Only receives results for its own requests
};

}  // namespace transport
```

