## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P3 · FEA · Claude-A

### Background: `exec::guarantee` in distributed individual interaction

In the pub/sub-loop world model, when a scheduler dispatches a batch of individual state updates to the transport layer, the caller needs to express constraints about how the transport processes those items. The `exec::guarantee` concept formalizes these constraints.

### Current problem

`transport::UnifiedWriter::write_batch(items)` currently provides no formal guarantee about:
1. Whether all items in the batch will be processed (some may be silently dropped under backpressure)
2. Whether the transport layer may reorder items within a batch
3. Whether the total number of items must be known upfront or can be streamed

This manifests as subtle bugs:

```cpp
// Bug scenario: individual state updates silently dropped
auto batch = world.collect_all_individual_states();  // 10,000 states
writer.write_batch(batch);
// Transport silently drops states 8,193-10,000 due to internal buffer limit
// No error reported — subscribers see a partial world snapshot
```

### Proposed design

Introduce two concepts from the DistributedCore execution model:

#### 1. `exec::guarantee` — what the transport promises

```cpp
namespace transport::exec {

enum class guarantee {
    // Transport may process fewer items than submitted
    // Caller must check return value for actual count
    best_effort,

    // Transport MUST process exactly the number of items submitted
    // If it cannot, it must report an error (not silently drop)
    all_or_error,

    // Transport MUST process all items AND preserve submission order
    // Individual states arrive at subscribers in the same order published
    ordered_all_or_error
};

// Writer that carries a guarantee as a compile-time property
template <typename T, guarantee G>
class GuaranteedWriter {
public:
    // For best_effort: returns actual number of items processed
    // For all_or_error: returns total or throws
    // For ordered_all_or_error: returns total and preserves order, or throws
    size_t write_batch(std::span<const T> items);
};

}  // namespace transport::exec
```

#### 2. `max_total_num_items` — capacity declaration

```cpp
namespace transport::exec {

// Declare the maximum number of items a transport channel can handle
// in a single batch. This is a contract between the scheduler and transport.
struct max_total_num_items {
    size_t value;

    // The scheduler uses this to partition work:
    // if world has 10,000 individuals and transport says max=4096,
    // scheduler splits into ceil(10000/4096) = 3 batches
};

// Query the transport channel's capacity
template <typename T>
max_total_num_items query_capacity(const UnifiedWriter<T>& writer);

// Example usage in scheduler:
void dispatch_world_tick(WorldState& world) {
    auto cap = exec::query_capacity(writer);
    auto individuals = world.all_individuals();

    for (size_t offset = 0; offset < individuals.size(); offset += cap.value) {
        auto batch = individuals.subspan(offset, 
            std::min(cap.value, individuals.size() - offset));

        auto processed = writer.write_batch(batch);
        assert(processed == batch.size());  // guaranteed by all_or_error
    }
}

}  // namespace transport::exec
```

### Integration with BackendRouter

Different transport backends have different natural capacities:

| Backend | Natural max_total_num_items | guarantee |
|---------|---------------------------|-----------|
| IntraProcess | unlimited (memory bound) | ordered_all_or_error |
| Shm | segment_size / sizeof(T) | all_or_error |
| RTPS/UDP | ~64 (MTU fragmentation) | best_effort |
| RTPS/TCP | ~4096 (TCP window) | all_or_error |

`BackendRouter` selects the batch size based on the backend's declared capacity and automatically partitions oversized batches.

