## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P2 🟢 · FEA · Claude-E

### Motivation

The `transport/message_format.h` header defines the wire format for individual state messages transmitted via Cyber RT's RTPS transport. This includes:
- `MessageHeader` — version, flags, publisher individual ID, sequence number
- `MessagePayload` — serialized individual state data
- `MessageTrailer` — CRC32 checksum, padding
- `FragmentHeader` — for messages exceeding RTPS MTU (fragmentation support)

Currently there are **zero verification tests** for this header. The format was implemented from the DDS/RTPS spec (OMG RTPS v2.3) but has never been tested against an independent parser. Any regression in field offsets, byte ordering, or alignment would silently corrupt inter-individual communication.

### What `.verify` tests are

Verification tests for message format headers test that:
1. Each struct has the expected `sizeof` and `alignof`
2. Each field has the expected `offsetof`
3. Byte ordering matches the wire spec (big-endian fields where RTPS requires)
4. Serialized output matches known-good reference vectors (golden test)

### Test design

```cpp
// transport/tests/message_format_verify.cpp

#include "transport/message_format.h"
#include <gtest/gtest.h>

TEST(MessageFormatVerify, HeaderLayout) {
    // Verify struct size matches RTPS spec
    static_assert(sizeof(transport::MessageHeader) == 24,
        "MessageHeader must be 24 bytes per RTPS v2.3 §8.3.3.1");

    // Verify field offsets
    static_assert(offsetof(transport::MessageHeader, protocol_version) == 0);
    static_assert(offsetof(transport::MessageHeader, vendor_id) == 4);
    static_assert(offsetof(transport::MessageHeader, individual_id) == 8);
    static_assert(offsetof(transport::MessageHeader, sequence_number) == 16);

    // Verify alignment
    static_assert(alignof(transport::MessageHeader) == 4,
        "MessageHeader must be 4-byte aligned for RTPS wire compatibility");
}

TEST(MessageFormatVerify, HeaderSerialization) {
    transport::MessageHeader header{};
    header.protocol_version = {2, 3};  // RTPS 2.3
    header.vendor_id = PUBSUB_LOOP_VENDOR_ID;
    header.individual_id = IndividualId{0x12345678, 0x9ABCDEF0};
    header.sequence_number = 42;

    // Serialize to bytes
    auto bytes = transport::serialize_header(header);

    // Golden reference: known-correct serialization of the above
    const uint8_t expected[] = {
        0x02, 0x03, 0x00, 0x00,  // protocol_version + padding
        // ... (full golden vector)
    };
    EXPECT_EQ(bytes, std::vector<uint8_t>(expected, expected + sizeof(expected)));
}

TEST(MessageFormatVerify, FragmentHeaderLayout) {
    // Fragment header adds 12 bytes to standard header
    static_assert(sizeof(transport::FragmentHeader) == 12);
    static_assert(offsetof(transport::FragmentHeader, fragment_number) == 0);
    static_assert(offsetof(transport::FragmentHeader, total_fragments) == 4);
    static_assert(offsetof(transport::FragmentHeader, fragment_size) == 8);
}

TEST(MessageFormatVerify, PayloadAlignment) {
    // After header + fragment header, payload must start at 4-byte boundary
    constexpr size_t header_size = sizeof(transport::MessageHeader);
    constexpr size_t frag_size = sizeof(transport::FragmentHeader);
    static_assert((header_size + frag_size) % 4 == 0,
        "Payload offset must be 4-byte aligned per RTPS spec");
}

TEST(MessageFormatVerify, TrailerCRC) {
    // Verify CRC32 computation matches reference implementation
    transport::MessageTrailer trailer;
    uint8_t test_payload[] = {0x01, 0x02, 0x03, 0x04};
    trailer.crc32 = transport::compute_crc32(test_payload, sizeof(test_payload));

    // CRC32 of {0x01, 0x02, 0x03, 0x04} = 0xB63CFBCD (IEEE 802.3)
    EXPECT_EQ(trailer.crc32, 0xB63CFBCD);
}

TEST(MessageFormatVerify, CrossPlatformEndianness) {
    // Verify big-endian fields are correctly byte-swapped on little-endian hosts
    transport::MessageHeader header{};
    header.sequence_number = 0x0000000000000001;

    auto bytes = transport::serialize_header(header);
    // sequence_number is big-endian in RTPS wire format
    // On little-endian host, bytes[16..23] should be: 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 01
    EXPECT_EQ(bytes[16], 0x00);
    EXPECT_EQ(bytes[23], 0x01);
}
```

