## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P2 🟢 · FEA · Claude-A

### Problem

The `transport::Barrier<thread_scope_block>` synchronization primitive is used within individual processing groups to coordinate parallel state updates. Currently it only supports barriers over **local** shared memory — all threads in the barrier must be on the same individual processing unit (IPU/SM) with direct access to the same shared memory region.

This breaks when an individual's state processing is distributed across multiple IPUs via the scheduler's work-splitting mechanism. For example, a large individual (carrying 10MB of mesh data) may have its state update split across 4 IPUs:

```
Individual X state update (10MB mesh):

  IPU 0           IPU 1           IPU 2           IPU 3
  ┌──────┐        ┌──────┐        ┌──────┐        ┌──────┐
  │Chunk 0│        │Chunk 1│        │Chunk 2│        │Chunk 3│
  │2.5MB  │        │2.5MB  │        │2.5MB  │        │2.5MB  │
  └───┬───┘        └───┬───┘        └───┬───┘        └───┬───┘
      │                │                │                │
      └────────────────┴────────────────┴────────────────┘
                    Need barrier synchronization
                    across IPU boundaries
                    (shared memory not accessible)
```

The current `Barrier<thread_scope_block>` cannot span this gap because each IPU has its own shared memory space.

### Proposed solution: remote shared memory barrier

Extend `Barrier` to support **remote shared memory** — a barrier backed by a memory region accessible across IPU boundaries:

```cpp
namespace transport {

// Extended barrier that can synchronize across IPU boundaries
// Uses distributed shared memory (DSM) or global memory fallback
template <thread_scope Scope>
class Barrier;

// Block-scope: existing implementation (local shared memory)
template <>
class Barrier<thread_scope_block> {
    // ... existing implementation unchanged
};

// System-scope: new implementation for cross-IPU synchronization
template <>
class Barrier<thread_scope_system> {
public:
    // Initialize with the total number of participating threads across all IPUs
    void init(uint32_t total_thread_count);

    // Arrive at the barrier — thread signals it has reached this point
    // Uses atomic operation on global memory (accessible from all IPUs)
    arrival_token arrive();

    // Wait for all participants to arrive
    // Spins on global memory atomic — higher latency than shared memory barrier
    void wait(arrival_token token);

    // Combined arrive + wait
    void arrive_and_wait();

private:
    // Barrier state in global memory (accessible from all IPUs)
    struct alignas(64) BarrierState {
        cuda::atomic<uint32_t, cuda::thread_scope_system> arrive_count;
        cuda::atomic<uint32_t, cuda::thread_scope_system> phase;
    };

    BarrierState* global_state_;  // pointer to global memory
};

// Block-scope with remote shared memory support
// Allows a block-scope barrier to be backed by memory from another IPU
// (via Hopper/Blackwell SM-to-SM shared memory access)
template <>
class Barrier<thread_scope_block>::with_remote_memory {
public:
    // Construct a barrier that uses remote shared memory from another IPU
    // `remote_smem` points to shared memory on a peer IPU
    // Requires hardware support (sm_90+ for Hopper, sm_100+ for Blackwell)
    with_remote_memory(void* remote_smem, uint32_t thread_count);

    arrival_token arrive();
    void wait(arrival_token token);

    // Check if hardware supports remote shared memory barriers
    static bool is_supported();
};

}  // namespace transport
```

### Use case: distributed individual state barrier

```cpp
// Scheduler splits Individual X's 10MB mesh update across 4 IPUs
// Each IPU processes 2.5MB chunk independently, then synchronizes

__global__ void process_large_individual_state(
    IndividualState* global_state,
    transport::Barrier<thread_scope_system>* barrier,
    int chunk_id, int num_chunks)
{
    // Phase 1: each IPU processes its chunk independently
    process_chunk(global_state, chunk_id);

    // Phase 2: barrier — wait for all IPUs to finish their chunks
    auto token = barrier->arrive();
    barrier->wait(token);

    // Phase 3: merge results (only IPU 0 does this)
    if (chunk_id == 0) {
        merge_chunks(global_state, num_chunks);
    }
}
```

### Performance characteristics

| Barrier type | Latency | Use case |
|-------------|---------|----------|
| `Barrier<thread_scope_block>` (local smem) | ~50ns | Single-IPU individual processing |
| `Barrier<thread_scope_block>::with_remote_memory` | ~200ns | Adjacent-IPU individual processing (Hopper+) |
| `Barrier<thread_scope_system>` (global mem) | ~2µs | Cross-IPU individual processing (any hardware) |

