## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P3 · DOC · Claude-E

### Problem

The `transport::async_contract_fulfillment` enum is used throughout the transport layer's async API to indicate how an asynchronous operation was completed, but it has **no documentation**. Developers encounter values like `async_contract_fulfillment::async` and `async_contract_fulfillment::sync` in error messages and profiler traces without understanding the semantics.

### Current definition (undocumented)

```cpp
// transport/async.h — current
namespace transport {
enum class async_contract_fulfillment {
    async,
    sync,
    none
};
}
```

### What each value means (to be documented)

```cpp
namespace transport {

/// Indicates how an asynchronous transport operation's contract was fulfilled.
///
/// When a pub/sub channel write or read is issued asynchronously, the transport
/// layer may complete the operation in one of three ways, depending on hardware
/// support, buffer availability, and channel configuration.
///
/// Example usage:
///   auto result = writer.write_async(state);
///   switch (result.fulfillment) {
///       case async_contract_fulfillment::async:
///           // Operation is in-flight — check barrier for completion
///           barrier.wait(result.token);
///           break;
///       case async_contract_fulfillment::sync:
///           // Operation completed immediately — data is already visible
///           break;
///       case async_contract_fulfillment::none:
///           // Operation was not performed — channel is in error state
///           handle_channel_error();
///           break;
///   }
enum class async_contract_fulfillment {
    /// The operation was initiated asynchronously and is still in progress.
    /// The caller must synchronize on the associated barrier or token
    /// before accessing the result.
    ///
    /// This is the expected path for:
    /// - Shared-memory writes with DMA/TMA hardware acceleration
    /// - RTPS writes to remote subscribers (network I/O)
    /// - Cross-partition individual state transfers
    ///
    /// The operation will complete when:
    /// - The barrier associated with the operation is reached
    /// - The associated cuda::barrier<> is arrived at
    /// - The associated transport::ReadFuture<T> becomes ready
    async,

    /// The operation completed synchronously — the data is already at its
    /// destination and visible to all observers.
    ///
    /// This happens when:
    /// - IntraProcess transport: pointer handoff is immediate
    /// - Small payloads (<64 bytes) that fit in a single cache line write
    /// - The destination buffer was already mapped and the copy was trivial
    /// - Hardware async path is unavailable and the transport fell back to
    ///   a synchronous memcpy
    ///
    /// The caller does NOT need to wait on any barrier — the data is ready.
    sync,

    /// The operation was NOT performed. No data was transferred.
    ///
    /// This happens when:
    /// - The channel is in an error state (subscriber died, segment unmapped)
    /// - Backpressure: the destination buffer is full and the write policy
    ///   is DROP_ON_FULL (not BLOCK_ON_FULL)
    /// - The individual that owns this channel has been evicted by the scheduler
    ///
    /// The caller should check the associated error code for details:
    ///   auto result = writer.write_async(state);
    ///   if (result.fulfillment == async_contract_fulfillment::none) {
    ///       LOG_ERROR("Write failed: {}", result.error_code);
    ///   }
    none
};

/// Result of an async transport operation
template <typename T>
struct AsyncResult {
    async_contract_fulfillment fulfillment;

    /// Valid only when fulfillment == async
    /// Use to synchronize: barrier.wait(token)
    std::optional<BarrierToken> token;

    /// Valid only when fulfillment == none
    /// Describes why the operation was not performed
    std::optional<TransportError> error_code;
};

}  // namespace transport
```

### Documentation deliverables

1. **Header doc comments** (above) — embedded in `transport/async.h`
2. **API reference page** — generated by `tools/docgen` from the header comments
3. **Usage guide** — a markdown document explaining the async write/read pattern:

```markdown
# Transport async operations

## Write patterns

### Fire-and-forget (best effort)
```cpp
auto result = writer.write_async(state);
// Don't check result — acceptable for non-critical state updates
// like individual visual animation states
```

### Write-and-sync (guaranteed delivery)
```cpp
auto result = writer.write_async(state);
if (result.fulfillment == async_contract_fulfillment::async) {
    barrier.wait(result.token.value());
}
// State is now visible to all subscribers
```

### Write-with-error-handling
```cpp
auto result = writer.write_async(state);
switch (result.fulfillment) {
    case async_contract_fulfillment::async:
        pending_writes.push_back(result.token.value());
        break;
    case async_contract_fulfillment::sync:
        // Already done
        break;
    case async_contract_fulfillment::none:
        if (result.error_code == TransportError::SUBSCRIBER_DEAD) {
            reconnect_channel();
        }
        break;
}
```
```

