## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P2 🟢 · FEA · Claude-D

### Problem

Individual state loading (`BlockLoad`) and storing (`BlockStore`) currently only work between global memory and registers. There is no path for loading individual state directly into shared memory (IPU local cache) or storing from shared memory back.

The current workflow requires two steps:

```
Step 1: global → registers (BlockLoad)
Step 2: registers → shared memory (manual __shared__ assignment)

// And for writes:
Step 3: shared memory → registers (manual read)
Step 4: registers → global (BlockStore)
```

This is wasteful because:
- Registers are scarce (255 per thread on current architectures). Loading a large individual state (e.g. 128 floats for a physics-enabled individual) consumes 128 registers just for staging, reducing occupancy.
- The copy through registers adds 2 extra data movement steps.

### Proposed API

```cpp
namespace transport {

// BlockLoad: load individual state directly from global into shared memory
template <typename T, int BlockSize, int ItemsPerThread,
          BlockLoadAlgorithm Algorithm = BLOCK_LOAD_DIRECT>
class BlockLoad {
public:
    // Existing: global → registers
    void Load(const T* global_ptr, T (&items)[ItemsPerThread]);

    // NEW: global → shared memory
    // Does NOT stage through registers — uses async copy (cp.async) on sm_80+
    void LoadToShared(const T* global_ptr, T* shared_ptr, int num_items);
};

// BlockStore: store from shared memory directly to global
template <typename T, int BlockSize, int ItemsPerThread,
          BlockStoreAlgorithm Algorithm = BLOCK_STORE_DIRECT>
class BlockStore {
public:
    // Existing: registers → global
    void Store(T* global_ptr, const T (&items)[ItemsPerThread]);

    // NEW: shared memory → global
    // Uses async writeback on sm_90+ (TMA store)
    void StoreFromShared(T* global_ptr, const T* shared_ptr, int num_items);
};

}  // namespace transport
```

### Implementation: cp.async path

On sm_80+ (Ampere and newer), `LoadToShared` uses the `cp.async` instruction which copies data from global memory directly into shared memory without consuming registers:

```cpp
template <typename T, int BlockSize, int ItemsPerThread>
void BlockLoad<T, BlockSize, ItemsPerThread>::LoadToShared(
    const T* global_ptr, T* shared_ptr, int num_items) 
{
    // Each thread loads its stripe directly to shared memory
    int tid = threadIdx.x;
    int stride = BlockSize;

    for (int i = tid; i < num_items; i += stride) {
        // cp.async: global → shared, bypasses registers
        cp_async_copy_global_to_shared(
            &shared_ptr[i], &global_ptr[i], sizeof(T));
    }

    // Wait for all async copies to complete
    cp_async_wait_all();
    __syncthreads();
}
```

### Use case: individual physics state processing

```cpp
__global__ void process_physics_state(
    IndividualPhysicsState* world_states,  // global memory
    int num_individuals)
{
    // Shared memory buffer for one individual's full state
    __shared__ IndividualPhysicsState local_state;

    int individual_idx = blockIdx.x;

    // NEW: load directly to shared memory — saves 128 registers
    transport::BlockLoad<float, 256, 1>::LoadToShared(
        reinterpret_cast<const float*>(&world_states[individual_idx]),
        reinterpret_cast<float*>(&local_state),
        sizeof(IndividualPhysicsState) / sizeof(float));

    // Process state in shared memory (all threads collaborate)
    integrate_physics(&local_state);

    // NEW: store directly from shared memory back to global
    transport::BlockStore<float, 256, 1>::StoreFromShared(
        reinterpret_cast<float*>(&world_states[individual_idx]),
        reinterpret_cast<const float*>(&local_state),
        sizeof(IndividualPhysicsState) / sizeof(float));
}
```

### Register pressure impact

| Approach | Registers per thread | Occupancy (256-thread block) |
|----------|---------------------|------------------------------|
| Current: global→registers→shared | 128 + 32 (overhead) = 160 | 25% (register-limited) |
| Proposed: global→shared (cp.async) | 32 (overhead only) | 75% (shared-mem-limited) |

3x occupancy improvement for physics-heavy individuals.

