Several world model algorithms in the `scheduler` module (`merge_sort` for spatial ordering of individuals, `unique_by_key` for deduplicating individual state entries) require shared memory as scratch space. Currently, the shared memory size is determined at compile time:

```cpp
// Current: fixed shared memory allocation
template <typename T, int BlockSize>
__global__ void merge_sort_individuals(T* data, int n) {
    __shared__ T scratch[BlockSize * 2];  // compile-time size
    // ...
}
```

This is inflexible because:
1. Different individual state types have different sizes — a `PositionState` (12 bytes) needs much less scratch than a `FullPhysicsState` (512 bytes)
2. The optimal amount of scratch depends on the IPU's available shared memory, which varies by architecture (sm_80: 164KB, sm_90: 228KB, sm_100: 228KB+)
3. Algorithms that could benefit from more scratch (multi-way merge, larger tile sorts) are artificially limited

### Proposed solution: virtual shared memory

Implement a "virtual shared memory" system that dynamically allocates shared memory at kernel launch time and falls back to global memory for the overflow:

```cpp
namespace transport {

// Virtual shared memory: uses hardware shared memory up to the limit,
// then transparently spills to global memory
template <typename T>
class VirtualSharedMemory {
public:
    // Allocate `count` elements
    // First `hw_capacity` elements are in hardware shared memory (fast)
    // Remaining elements are in global memory (slower, but unlimited)
    __device__ VirtualSharedMemory(
        T* hw_shared_ptr,     // pointer to __shared__ region
        size_t hw_capacity,   // how many T fit in hardware shared memory
        T* global_spill_ptr,  // pointer to pre-allocated global memory spill buffer
        size_t total_count    // total elements needed
    );

    // Transparent access — caller doesn't know if element is in smem or gmem
    __device__ T& operator[](size_t idx) {
        if (idx < hw_capacity_) {
            return hw_shared_ptr_[idx];
        } else {
            return global_spill_ptr_[idx - hw_capacity_];
        }
    }

    // Performance hint: is this element in fast shared memory?
    __device__ bool is_fast(size_t idx) const { return idx < hw_capacity_; }

private:
    T* hw_shared_ptr_;
    T* global_spill_ptr_;
    size_t hw_capacity_;
};

}  // namespace transport
```

### Integration with merge_sort for individual spatial ordering

```cpp
// merge_sort using virtual shared memory
template <typename T>
__global__ void merge_sort_individuals_vsm(
    T* data, int n,
    T* global_spill,          // pre-allocated global memory
    int hw_smem_elements)     // determined at launch time
{
    extern __shared__ T dynamic_smem[];  // dynamic shared memory

    transport::VirtualSharedMemory<T> scratch(
        dynamic_smem, hw_smem_elements,
        global_spill + blockIdx.x * (n / gridDim.x),  // per-block spill region
        n / gridDim.x  // total elements this block handles
    );

    // Algorithm uses scratch[i] transparently
    // Hot data stays in shared memory, cold data spills to global
    for (int stride = 1; stride < tile_size; stride *= 2) {
        merge_step(scratch, stride, tile_size);
        __syncthreads();
    }
}

// Launch with dynamic shared memory sized to hardware capacity
void launch_merge_sort(T* data, int n) {
    int smem_per_block = query_max_dynamic_smem(device);
    int hw_elements = smem_per_block / sizeof(T);

    T* global_spill;
    cudaMalloc(&global_spill, n * sizeof(T));  // spill buffer

    merge_sort_individuals_vsm<<<grid, block, smem_per_block>>>(
        data, n, global_spill, hw_elements);
}
```

### Integration with unique_by_key for individual state dedup

```cpp
// unique_by_key: remove duplicate individual states in a sorted sequence
// Individuals with the same position hash are candidates for merge
template <typename KeyT, typename ValueT>
__global__ void unique_by_key_vsm(
    KeyT* keys, ValueT* values, int n,
    KeyT* key_spill, ValueT* val_spill,
    int hw_smem_keys)
{
    extern __shared__ char smem[];
    KeyT* smem_keys = reinterpret_cast<KeyT*>(smem);
    ValueT* smem_vals = reinterpret_cast<ValueT*>(smem + hw_smem_keys * sizeof(KeyT));

    transport::VirtualSharedMemory<KeyT> vkeys(
        smem_keys, hw_smem_keys, key_spill, /* total */ ...);

    // Deduplicate using virtual shared memory
    // Duplicate individual states are merged (e.g. average positions)
}
```

### Performance characteristics

| Scenario | Pure shared memory | Virtual shared memory |
|----------|-------------------|----------------------|
| Data fits in smem | 100% smem speed | 100% smem speed (no spill) |
| Data 2x smem capacity | Cannot run (crash/wrong results) | ~70% smem speed (50% spills) |
| Data 10x smem capacity | Cannot run | ~30% smem speed (90% spills) |

The key insight: even with significant spill, virtual shared memory is faster than a purely global-memory algorithm because the hot working set stays in shared memory.

