## Description

@pub-sub-loop-transport · P3 · Todo · Claude-D

### Bug report

`compute-sanitizer` (CUDA's memory-access and race-condition detection tool) reports an invalid shared memory read in the `DeviceScanKernel` when running on Blackwell architecture (sm_120a). The kernel is used by the transport layer for prefix-scan operations on individual state sequences (e.g. computing cumulative positions for spatial indexing).

### Sanitizer output

```
========= Invalid __shared__ read of size 4 bytes
=========     at transport::DeviceScanKernel<float, 256, ScanOp::ADD>+0x1a8
=========     by thread (128, 0, 0) in block (7, 0, 0)
=========     Address 0x00007f8000001800 is out of bounds
=========     Saved host backtrace up to driver entry point at kernel launch time
=========     Host Frame:launch_scan_kernel [transport/scan_kernels.cu:142]
```

### Analysis

The invalid read occurs in the "warpspeed" variant of `DeviceScanKernel`, which uses an aggressive optimization where warps read ahead into the next tile's shared memory to overlap computation with data loading. On sm_120a (Blackwell), the warp scheduling model differs from Hopper:

1. **Hopper (sm_90)**: warps within a block execute in a round-robin schedule. The "read ahead" optimization works because warp 4 reading from warp 5's shared memory region is safe — warp 5 has already written its data in the previous scheduling round.

2. **Blackwell (sm_120a)**: the warp scheduler is more aggressive about concurrent warp execution. Warp 4 and warp 5 may execute simultaneously, and warp 4's "read ahead" into warp 5's region races with warp 5's write.

The result is an out-of-bounds read or a data race, depending on timing. `compute-sanitizer` catches the out-of-bounds case; the data race case produces silently wrong scan results.

### Root cause

```cpp
// In DeviceScanKernel warpspeed variant:
template <typename T, int BlockSize>
__global__ void DeviceScanKernel_Warpspeed(T* data, int n, T* block_sums) {
    __shared__ T smem[BlockSize + 32];  // +32 for warp read-ahead padding

    int tid = threadIdx.x;
    int warp_id = tid / 32;
    int lane = tid % 32;

    // Load my tile
    smem[tid] = data[blockIdx.x * BlockSize + tid];
    __syncthreads();

    // Intra-warp scan
    T val = smem[tid];
    for (int offset = 1; offset < 32; offset *= 2) {
        T neighbor = __shfl_up_sync(0xFFFFFFFF, val, offset);
        if (lane >= offset) val += neighbor;
    }
    smem[tid] = val;
    __syncthreads();

    // BUG: warpspeed read-ahead — reads smem[tid + 32]
    // which is the next warp's data
    // On Blackwell, this races with the next warp's write above
    if (warp_id < (BlockSize / 32 - 1)) {
        T next_warp_sum = smem[(warp_id + 1) * 32 + 31]; // ← INVALID READ on sm_120a
        // ...
    }
}
```

### Fix

Replace the read-ahead optimization with a properly synchronized cross-warp reduction:

```cpp
// Fix: use an explicit cross-warp reduction buffer with proper sync
template <typename T, int BlockSize>
__global__ void DeviceScanKernel_Fixed(T* data, int n, T* block_sums) {
    constexpr int NUM_WARPS = BlockSize / 32;

    __shared__ T smem[BlockSize];
    __shared__ T warp_sums[NUM_WARPS];  // explicit warp sum buffer

    int tid = threadIdx.x;
    int warp_id = tid / 32;
    int lane = tid % 32;

    // Load and intra-warp scan (same as before)
    smem[tid] = data[blockIdx.x * BlockSize + tid];
    __syncthreads();

    T val = smem[tid];
    for (int offset = 1; offset < 32; offset *= 2) {
        T neighbor = __shfl_up_sync(0xFFFFFFFF, val, offset);
        if (lane >= offset) val += neighbor;
    }

    // Each warp's last lane writes its sum to the explicit buffer
    if (lane == 31) {
        warp_sums[warp_id] = val;
    }
    __syncthreads();  // ← ensures all warp sums are written before cross-warp scan

    // Cross-warp scan on warp_sums (single warp does this)
    if (warp_id == 0 && lane < NUM_WARPS) {
        T wsum = warp_sums[lane];
        for (int offset = 1; offset < NUM_WARPS; offset *= 2) {
            T neighbor = __shfl_up_sync(0xFFFFFFFF, wsum, offset);
            if (lane >= offset) wsum += neighbor;
        }
        warp_sums[lane] = wsum;
    }
    __syncthreads();  // ← ensures cross-warp scan complete before final add

    // Add preceding warps' sums
    if (warp_id > 0) {
        val += warp_sums[warp_id - 1];
    }

    smem[tid] = val;
    // ...
}
```

### Affected individual state operations

| Operation | Uses DeviceScanKernel | Impact of bug |
|-----------|----------------------|---------------|
| Spatial index construction | Prefix sum of cell counts | Wrong cell boundaries → missed collision detections |
| Load balancing | Prefix sum of individual weights | Uneven partition sizes → scheduler stalls |
| History sequence numbering | Prefix sum of per-channel message counts | Sequence gaps → subscriber misses state updates |

## Dependencies

- Requires: sm_120a (Blackwell) hardware for reproduction
- Fix must also be validated on sm_90 (Hopper) to ensure no regression
- Affects: `data::SpatialIndex`, `scheduler::LoadBalancer`, `transport::HistoryCache`

